1. The Core Libraries

    PyQt6.QtWidgets

        Definition: The visual toolkit required to construct a desktop graphical user interface (GUI).

        Usage: It provides the raw materials (the window, the buttons, the text boxes) used to
               build the physical appearance of the calculator.

    sys

        Definition: A system-level module that allows the Python script to communicate directly with the computer's operating system.

        Usage: It is used to capture command-line arguments when the app is launched (sys.argv) and
                to securely terminate the application process when the user clicks the "X" to close the window (sys.exit()).

2. The Application Elements (Widgets)

    QApplication

        Definition: The core background engine that runs the entire visual program.

        Usage: It manages the graphical control flow and main settings.
                No PyQt6 window can appear on a screen without this engine running first.

    QWidget

        Definition: The blank canvas. It is the most basic, empty window element in the PyQt framework.

        Usage: It acts as the foundational container that holds all the other buttons and labels.

    QGridLayout

        Definition: An invisible organizational tool that arranges elements into strict rows and columns, like a spreadsheet.

        Usage: It forces the labels, text boxes, and dropdown menus to align perfectly on the screen using
                coordinate points (e.g., placing the calculate button at row 2, column 0).

    QLabel

        Definition: A static text element.

        Usage: It is used to display non-editable instructions on the screen (like "Enter Value :") and
                to output the final calculated result to the user.

    QLineEdit

        Definition: A single-line blank text box.

        Usage: It allows the user to physically type their number into the application.

    QComboBox

        Definition: A clickable dropdown menu.

        Usage: It provides the user with a restricted list of choices (Feet or Centimeters) so they cannot type an invalid unit.

    QPushButton

        Definition: A standard, clickable digital button.

        Usage: It acts as the trigger mechanism. When clicked, it fires a signal that tells the application to run the math equations.

3. The Custom Classes and Methods

    Class: Calculator (Inherits from QWidget)

        Definition: The custom blueprint that defines the complete physical window and the logic of the converter.

        Usage: It bundles the visual layout (the grid) and the mathematical logic (the conversion) into one single, reusable object.

    Method: __init__

        Definition: The constructor method. This is the setup phase that runs automatically the exact millisecond the Calculator is created.

        Usage: It builds the physical interface. It sets the window title, creates the grid,
                summons all the widgets (labels, boxes, buttons), places them into the grid,
                and connects the "Convert" button to the math function.

    Method: calculate

        Definition: The operational logic engine. This function only runs when the "Convert" button is physically clicked.

        Usage: It extracts the raw text from the input box, forces it to become a decimal number (float),
                checks which unit is selected in the dropdown menu, performs the appropriate multiplication or division,
                 and updates the text on the screen. It also contains error handling (try/except) to prevent the program
                  from crashing if the user types a letter instead of a number.